{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Deliveries: Stable through 2023–24, followed by a clear surplus in early 2025, with ~4,900 more facility deliveries than expected (+6.7%).

PNC visits: Multiple disruptions below expected levels in 2023–24, followed by an increase in 2025 that brings volumes closer to or above expected trends.

Because PNC typically follows delivery trends, we would expect these indicators to move together — and in 2025, we see deliveries rising modestly while PNC shows a stronger rebound after earlier disruptions."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"5a53efc1-d170-4285-bf1e-4d9b37cba5d9","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Deliveries show surplus in 2025, while PNC recovers after earlier disruptions"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":" Clients counselled for FP fluctuated between a low of ~183,000 in Jan 2024 to a high of ~228,000 in Sep 2024, decreasing slightly to ~213,000 by the end of 2025. 

Clients initiated on modern contraceptive methods and adolescent modern contraceptive users followed similar trends, peaking in Sep 2024, followed by declines from Nov-Feb and increasing over 2025 to reach 15,200 and 32,300 users respectively. 

On average, modern-method users are ~13% of those counselled, indicating a persistent conversion gap from counselling to uptake.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":0.8,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"79296530-bc76-4be3-b81d-f1b5f514b2e6","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in family planning indicators","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Adolescents counselled for FP was stable without any notable variations in from Q3 2023 to Q3 2025.

Adolescents initiated on modern contraceptive methods and adolescent modern contraceptive users had more frequent fluctuation, with >10% surges in Q2 2024 for both, an extra surge in Q3 2024 for initiations only, and growth again in Q3 2025; both declined in Q1 2024 and Q1 2025.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"526bdc78-0d59-4e76-a1d5-b96e11107ff4","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Quarter-to-quarter change in service volume                                                                                  
Adolescent family planning indicators","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":0.8,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Wide variation across counties: While some counties show large surpluses across several indicators (e.g., Maryland, Margibi, Sinoe), others exhibit consistent shortfalls (e.g., Gbarpolu, Grand Gedeh, River Gee), indicating uneven recovery and service performance.

Indicator-specific patterns differ by county: Counties that overperform on maternal and child health indicators (e.g., ANC, deliveries, immunization) are not always the same counties that overperform on outpatient care or malaria treatment — highlighting distinct service delivery dynamics at the subnational level.

Some counties show mixed performance within the same service area: For example, a county may exceed expectations on one immunization indicator yet fall below on another, suggesting potential bottlenecks in supply chains, reporting, or service readiness that vary locally."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.6,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"07a38e41-6675-4ee6-91c8-c5cb158702a4","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Large county-level disparities in performance highlight the need to understand local drivers of both service gains and gaps"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"OPD new cases >5 years: After some disruptions in 2023, volumes rose steadily through 2024 and into 2025, reaching a clear surplus by mid-2025 (≈ 9% above expected, ~102,000 additional cases).

OPD new cases <5 years: Trends are flatter, with modest disruptions in late 2023 and small surpluses emerging in 2025 (≈ 5% above expected, ~23,000 additional cases).

OPD visits are stabilizing, with both age groups showing recovery by 2025, though the rebound is more pronounced among older children and adults than under-fives."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"30608f3a-f447-4445-be1a-44e1cd8bb73c","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"OPD visits rose above expected levels in 2025, with a stronger rebound among older children and adults than under-fives."}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Deliveries: Stable through 2023–24, followed by a clear surplus in early 2025, with ~1,200 more facility deliveries than expected per month (+9.6%), followed by a moderate decline mid-2025, though still near expected levels by September.

PNC visits: Multiple disruptions below expected levels in 2023–24, followed by an an increase and subsequent decrease in 2025 that brought volumes closer to expected trends. 

Because PNC typically follows delivery trends, we would expect these indicators to move together, and in 2025, we see both indicators following the same trends, with institutional deliveries reaching a surplus."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"5a53efc1-d170-4285-bf1e-4d9b37cba5d9","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Deliveries show surplus in 2025, while PNC recovered after earlier disruptions"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Diarrhea and pneumonia cases show episodic surges, rather than consistent seasonal patterns. The most pronounced spike occurred in March–April 2025.

At their peak, pneumonia cases reached ~17,200 and diarrhea ~15,200, well above typical monthly levels.

These spikes point to a sharp, short-term increase in disease burden, likely straining health facilities during early 2025.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"3c9bde14-c833-4e63-b01f-73f672a75b92","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in child illness cases","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"ANC1 vs ANC4 is mostly consistent, though a few counties (Grand Gedeh, Rivercess, and Sinoe) fall below 90%, suggesting misreporting in one of the indicators.

Delivery vs BCG is weak in all counties, likely influenced by ~19% of births at home; home-born infants later vaccinated can make BCG counts exceed deliveries.

Penta1 vs Penta3 is variable, with some counties >90% but others near 60%, pointing to gaps in recording successive doses."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"fe4382ac-324e-435f-a664-78d3c2e41221","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Internal consistency"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":0.8,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Family planning counseling showed persistent shortfalls through 2025, with a substantial disruption in September 2025 (~20% below expected), representing ~52,000 fewer clients counseled than anticipated.

FP initiations and FP new-and-continuing users exhibited more moderate fluctuations, with occasional deficits earlier in the period but shifting to small surpluses by mid-2025, including +14% and +12% surpluses in September 2025, respectively.

Overall FP service trends in 2025 indicate uneven recovery across indicators — with deep, sustained deficits in counseling volumes but improving performance for initiation and continuation, suggesting different bottlenecks across FP service components."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.7,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"93349568-e5db-4ac1-a72a-daa1e496f986","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Family planning service trends in 2025 were uneven, with sustained counseling shortfalls alongside improving initiation and continuation"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Trends for adolescent counseling for FP were volatile, with repeated declines below expected levels, including a disruption in September 2025 (~11% decline).

Adolescents initiated on modern contraceptive methods and adolescent modern contraceptive users had more frequent fluctuation and followed similar trends, with average disruptions of ~30% for initiations and ~31% for modern-method users, respectively, improving slightly in Jul–Sep 2025.

Adolescent family planning indicators reflect irregular patterns and instability, pointing to challenges in ensuring consistent adolescent reproductive health services."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.7,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"1fed8929-2500-4079-81f0-1ab4a8a0f163","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Adolescent family planning indicators show fluctuations, but overall trends remain flat through 2025, suggesting no major systemic change"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"Nationally, average overall scores remain modest (78–83%), showing that only a limited share of facility-months meet all data quality criteria at the same time.

Performance varies widely across counties: some (e.g., Bong, Grand Bassa, and Margibi) regularly exceed 90%, while others (e.g., River Gee, Rivercess, Sinoe) often remain below 70%.

Improvements are visible in several counties from 2024 to 2025 (e.g., Bomi, Bong, Grand Cape Mount, and Montserrado), but persistent gaps remain."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"b0a450d6-6a1b-40e7-962d-696aab759198","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Adolescents counselled for FP fluctuated between a low of ~37,300 in Jan 2024 to a high of ~45,100 in Sep 2024.

Adolescents initiated on modern contraceptive methods and adolescent modern contraceptive users followed similar trends, with the largest declines from Dec 2024 to Jan 2025, recovering by Sept 2025 to ~5,100 and ~9,400 users respectively. 

